 <br>
However, several past presidential advisers have testified before Congress and/or congressional committees, including Sandy Berger, Clinton's NSA, and Tom Ridge, who was on Bush's staff before Homeland Security was created.<br>
<br>
And given the critical importance of exploring the events surrounding 9/11 fully and publicly, and especially given Bush's previous efforts to derail and stall congressional inquiry into 9/11, I think invoking executive privilege here would have been spurious.<br>
<br>
Apparently Bush eventually agreed, since he bowed to pressure and allowed her to testify after all.<br>
<br>
Read Rice's testimony yourself, then tell me that Bush isn't hiding anything.<br>
<br>
