<br>
I'm not a big fan of Bush, I'm pretty middle of the road when it comes to politics. <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->   <br>
<br>
But...when the question comes up of if we are safer now, I think the answer really depends on from which direction the attacks would be coming from.<br>
<br>
Without a question, the governments/leaders of small countries are going to be more concerned about publicly supporting terrorists or their infrastructure now, simply because they are unsure if the USA will move in and do this a third time.<br>
<br>
It's a credible threat, the USA has replaced two governments now.<br>
<br>
Obviously it was a concern of Khadafi, and more likely than not what prompted all of the problems with North Korea leading up to the invasion of Iraq.<br>
<br>
The real question will be if in the long run, making so many little governments afraid of the USA, is a good thing or a bad thing. My vote is probably a bad thing.<br>
<br>
As for the weapons of mass destruction, I'm not sure why this keeps being brought up, time and time again. Sure he had them, he used them on the Kurds. The problem is though, the likelyhood of him using them against us our our allies is really low. Example, he tries to gas the Israelis and ends up getting nuked by them, not a very good exchange, I'm thinking. <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->   <br>
<br>
Saddam was definitely a nut, but their are worse out there. If he had to go, my feelings are we should have killed him and then left the Iraqis with the knowledge that if he's replaced by someone of the same calibur, we'll do it again.<br>
<br>
Arleny<br>
